div.p:
3. For Example; Common places for Arguments;
* To prove any thing to be good, may be such as
these;—



The proud oftentation of mens abilities for Invention;
and the vain affectation of varieties for expressions,
merit not the name, &c.



Hypponax similis est vespae; non magnum quidem murmur
excitat, sed acriter pungit: Demosthenes, tibiis;
quibus si collum demas, reliquum erit inutile.—

Quo fit ut scribere longiores epistolas nolim, velim legere;
illud tanquam delicatus, hoc tanquam ociosus: nihil
est enim aut pigrius delicatis, aut curiosius ociosis.

(Adhuc pejor est [ad impediendum
intellectum] mistura verborum, qualis
in illo versu;
